<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-3509" src="https://ideaing-ideas.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/2016/04/19-1.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="467" /></p>
&nbsp;

Having a home security system is the most logical addition to your home where safety is concerned.

&nbsp;
<h2>About Home Security Systems</h2>
&nbsp;

Home security systems are devices designed to protect your home fromÂ burglars. While there are many different options when it comes to these systems, their primary concept is twofold:

1. To deter predators from ever attempting to enter your home.

2. To alert the homeowner, and often the local authorities, about any attempted or successful burglary.

3. To record evidence for law enforcement. (Video footage can help identify aÂ thief, which in turn can help catch them and get any lost property returned to you!)
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-3484" src="https://ideaing-ideas.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/2016/04/1.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="467" /></p>
Statistically, your home is less likely to be targeted if criminals know that a home security system is in place. Time and opportunity are two of the biggest factors in predators' minds when choosing a target. If they see that your home is difficult to enter, or that they'll have to circumvent a loud alarm system, they're much more likely to move on to a home that is less secure. (To this end, it is a good idea to place stickers on your windows or small signs in your front yard stating that you have a security system in place.)

Hopefully, signaling that you have an alarm system in place is enough to protect your home. However, if a burglar is more advanced, or has some deeper motivation for entering your space, then the security system you choose becomes much more important.

In my own experience, installing a variety of products that increase the security profile of your home is the best way to go.

&nbsp;
<h2>Options in the Home Security Market: What System is Right for You?</h2>
&nbsp;

There are many options within the home security market, and you'll find a wide range of opinions about which are best for ensuring your home's safety. These options have expanded tenfold in recent years with the advent of smart home technology.

The two biggest options within these systems are:

<strong>1. Professional Installation vs. Out-of-the-Box.Â </strong>More traditional and complex systems may require a professional installation, though even larger companies usually offer an out-of-the-box option for users who feel they can manage their own installation. Smart home security hubs typically fall under the out-of-the-box category, but installation is often quite simple.
<ul>
 	<li><strong>Pros of professional installation</strong>: The system will be installed easily and you can be sure that it will work correctly. A professional can provide insight into what products you need, and you'll have someone to call if things stop working properly.</li>
 	<li><strong>Pros of out-of-the-box installation</strong>: You'll be more aware of how the products work, and installation is typically a fairly simple DIY project. You'll also usually spend less money, and can choose specific products that you know your home needs rather than being sold too much by an employee working on commission.</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

<strong>2. Professional Home Monitoring vs. Smart Phone Application Monitoring.Â </strong>Additionally, you can choose between having a company manage your home security device (ie, popular options like <a href="http://www.frontlinesecurity.com" target="_blank">Frontline</a> and <a href="http://www.adthouseprotection.com" target="_blank">ADT</a>) or you can manage the system independently with a smart phone application.
<ul>
 	<li><strong>Pros of Professional Home Monitoring</strong>: You'll have a extra set of eyes on your home at all times, and in the event that you are somehow unable to respond to a threat (if you are traveling, Â or somehow incapacitated) this is a fail-safe option.</li>
 	<li><strong>Pros of Smart Phone Application Monitoring</strong>: This is a less expensive option, and allows you to have more control over watching your own home. Some people don't like the idea of giving their home's access to a major company, and are more comfortable taking matters into their own hands. Additionally, professional monitoring systems have a high rate of false alarms (anything from high winds to a pet can accidentally set off an alarm.) If the police are called to your home for multiple false alarms you could be fined. Smart home monitoring allows you to make the judgement call on calling the authorities.</li>
</ul>
I consider myself to be fairly tech-savvy, but certainly not a master of new technology. I am also someone who likes to be in control of my own home and the products within it. Because of this, going the route of smart home monitoring rather than relying solely on a third party company made the most sense.

&nbsp;
<h2>Average Pricing for Home Security Systems</h2>
&nbsp;

If you're looking at a professionally installed and monitored system, you could also be looking at spending quite a bit. <a href="http://money.usnews.com/money/personal-finance/articles/2013/09/09/the-cost-of-keeping-your-home-safe" target="_blank">Average costs</a> of equipment installation from larger companies range from $600 - $1,200, though sometimes you can find a good introductory sale. After the installation, the average cost for monthly home monitoring fees is $30, which works out to about $360/year.

If you've decided to go the out-of-the-box route, there are a variety of products that you can choose from which will add to your expenses, though a basic system is considerably less than one from one of the larger companies. We've chosen products that display the range of options that smart home security systems cover today. As we mentioned, building your own system in this way allows you to choose items which are specific to your home and customize your security capabilities.
